title: For Sale:  USED - Heckler & Koch SR9TC 7.62x51mm NATO
postcontent:
We have a used Heckler & Koch SR9TC in 7.62x51mm NATO for sale.
This gun is in like new condition and does not appear to have been fired since leaving H&K.
The 1989 Import Ban, enacted by President George H. W. Bush, bans from importation all semi-automatic rifles with a folding or telescoping stock, separate pistol grip, bipod, ability to accept a bayonet, grenade launcher, night sights, or flash suppressor. The HK 91, 93 and 94 models were all on the import ban list.  At the time of the ban, about 130 or so HK91s had already been delivered to the U.S. but had not yet cleared customs. H&K complied with the ban by renaming those HK91s as HK911 (basically stamping another "1" after the name) and adding a Bell-Carlson thumbhole stock. H&K was also required to put a spot weld over the end cap detent because the ATF considered the hole to be a bayonet lug. This prevented addition of the bayonet. The HK911 did have the standard HK91 threaded barrel but this was covered by a pinned thread hider/cover.
The HK911 eventually turned into the SR9 in 1990 which had the new 20-inch polygonal barrel. The first SR9s imported had wood grain stocks. The SR9 was also referred to as the "Orion." Soon, H&K switched to black stocks. Right after the black stock guns were brought in, H&K also included a standard 91 stock set along with the SR9 thumbhole mounted stock set.
HK SR9T Receiver.
Then the “T” and “TC” models got in, even though they had pistol grips. They got exempted as they were then thought of as target rifles of the currently allowed SR9 series. President Bill Clinton pulled the plug on the importation of all HK SR9s on April 6, 1998 because they could accept a standard capacity magazine.
There were a total of 125 TC’s. Initially 25 were made in response to requests for an SR9T with the PSG1 buttstock. H&K did not have these in their catalog. The next year, HK added the SR9TC to their catalog and imported 100 guns. They were marked "TC" in Virginia as were the SR9T’s. In 1989 the BATF had not determined what was considered acceptable as to what grips were fitted to the rifles by H&K USA the new rules were not set to be "in-force" until November 1990. For years, it was acceptable to reconfigure standard SR9 rifles to a T or TC configuration. T and TC rifles were probably not imported in that configuration and that is why the receivers are hand stamped and not finished. The stamping was done at H&K USA.

We believe that this indeed a fine example of a SR9TC; although there is no further documentation with the rifle.  This gun is in like new condition and does not appear to have been fired since leaving H&K.  You will not find a cleaner example from the SR9 TC series of rifles.  There have not been any imported since 1998.
This gun is also for sale in the store.  Please contact us for more information.

title: For Sale:  Springfield M1 Garand Type II National Match 1962       Documented NM DCM gun ME/TE of 1+ NICE NR!
postcontent:
A very scarce document Springfield M1 Garand Type II National Match Rifle. Serial number of 5834111 which is documented in Bruce Canfield’s excellent book title “The M1 Garand Rifle” as a National Match Rifle alo3ng with 1979 club gun document showing it on loan from the DCM. This one ended up being sold to the WEAN Gun Club in October of 1982. This is an all correct Type II national match with the following features:

2-52 SA marked barrel that is also T proofed (for targeted), NM marked twice and star marked. ME a of 1+ with TE of 1.5 with beautiful shiny bore.

NM marked series 77 SA marked Op Rod

Correct BME NM marked windage knob with hooded aperture sight marked NM/2 on sight baseand correct marked NM marked front sight marked .062

65 SA series bolt

Gas cylinder has small NM mark on bottom

mixed trigger group including 55 SA series hammer and unmarked safety. Floor of trigger guard is numbered and matches rifle

Glass bedded stock with proper P proof and Springfield DoD stamp and this is also numbered to the gun. The stock has very few minor bumps and looks to have been lighted sanded and possibly coated with a light oil...more than likely done by the gun club or new owner after released from the DCM. Like every NM I’ve handled the stock has zero wiggle in the handguards and fits very tight to the receiver.

This is an excellent example of a documented Type II National Match rifle specific to the 1962 Springfield Armory specs. Considered some of the finest and most accurate government arsenal competition quality M1’s rifles every made as each part was hand selected for fit and each barrel tested for accuracy. After discontinuing sales in 1973 many of these were taken apart when on loan to Greece so there are not many originals left. If you want the pinnacle of M1 garand manufacture the National Match is the rifle for you. Offered with NO RESERVE!

title: For Sale/Trade:  M&P 45 w/ NS, SS Match Threaded Barrel, and 5 mags.
postcontent:
Just like it sounds, Factory NS, Stainless Storm Lake Match grade threaded barrel, 2 factory 10 rd mags, 3 factory 15 round extended mags, factory backstraps, box and papers. The M&P 45 is an adjustable ergonomic polymer gun that is more comfortable to many than the Glock or XD. I won't debate merits vs de-merits, so if you like this type and feel, this is a good one.

Took this on a trade, and decided I shoot my 1911s in that caliber, so it doesn't get used. No factory barrel, but the replacement Storm Lake is nicer, more expensive, and allows screw-on compensators or a suppressor if you are NFA inclined. The sights are extremely bright. I believe S&W uses Metrolights which appear brighter than my brand new Trijicon H3's. Excellent for a sight picture in the dark.

I'm interested in selling outright, trading even swap, partial trade - up or down. If you have something interesting I'll hear you out.

I'm expecting a used gun price. This weapon goes for $600 @ Bud's when in stock, the factory barrel sells on eBay for around $50, but I'll assume it's a $100 loss. The mags run about $50 each (x3), and the Storm Lake barrel is around $200.

600+200+150=950... - 100 = 850 retail. Times 70% value for being used... comes to $600. So I'll assume $600 is around fair. I'll entertain offers of up or down - just don't tell me your trade is "worth _____" if you can't actually sell it for that. You be reasonable, I'll be reasonable.
